Sure! Here is some sample code for a simple Flappy Bird-like game in Unity:
```
using UnityEngine;

public class FlappyBird : MonoBehaviour
{
    // The force applied to the bird when the player jumps
    public float jumpForce = 100f;

    // The bird's Rigidbody2D component
    private Rigidbody2D rb;

    void Start()
    {
        // Get the bird's Rigidbody2D component
        rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody2D>();
    }

    void Update()
    {
        // If the space key is pressed...
        if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Space))
        {
            // ... add a force to the bird in the up direction.
            rb.AddForce(Vector2.up * jumpForce);
        }
    }
}
```
This code simply adds a force to the bird's Rigidbody2D component in the up direction when the space key is pressed. This will make the bird jump.

Of course, this is just a starting point, and there is much more you can do to make the game more interesting, such as adding obstacles, scoring, and so on. But this should give you a good starting point for creating your own Flappy Bird-like game in Unity.

I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.

You are correct that the code I provided could potentially lead to a memory leak if there are errors or timeouts that prevent the browser from closing properly. To address this, you can use a `try...finally` block to ensure that the browser is always closed, even if an error occurs.

Here is an updated version of the code that uses a `try...finally` block:
```javascript
const puppeteer = require('puppeteer');

(async () => {
  let browser;
  try {
    browser = await puppeteer.launch();
    const page = await browser.newPage();

    await page.goto('https://www.copart.com');

    // Click on "Login" button
    await page.click('#header-signin-link');

    // Fill in the login form
    await page.type('#username', 'your_username_here');
    await page.type('#password', 'your_password_here');

    // Click on "Sign in" button
    await Promise.all([
      page.waitForNavigation(),
      page.click('#login-form > button'),
    ]);

    // Wait for the user dashboard page to load
    await page.waitForSelector('#user-dashboard');

    // Log in successful, print a message
    console.log('Logged in successfully!');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error);
  } finally {
    if (browser) {
      await browser.close();
    }
  }
})();
```
In this version, we use a `let` variable to store the browser instance outside of the `try` block, and then we use a `finally` block to ensure that the browser is closed, even if there is an error or timeout. If an error occurs, we log the error to the console but still ensure that the browser is closed properly.

