Here is an example of a JavaScript function that can transform an object with keys in the format "order\_banners.X.text" to an array of objects with "id" and "text" properties:
```
function transformObjectToArray(obj) {
    const result = [];
    for (const key in obj) {
        const [, id, prop] = key.split('.');
        if (!result[id - 1]) {
            result[id - 1] = {};
        }
        result[id - 1][prop] = obj[key];
    }
    return result;
}
```
You can use this function like this:
```
const obj = { "order_banners.1.text": 'text1', "order_banners.2.text": 'text2' };
const result = transformObjectToArray(obj);
console.log(result);
```
This will output:
```
[{ text: 'text1' }, { text: 'text2' }]
```
You can add the ID key to the array by adding
```
result[id - 1].id = id;
```
This will output:
```
[{id: 1, text: 'text1' }, {id: 2, text: 'text2' }]
```
Please note that this implementation assumes that the keys of the input object are in the format "order\_banners.X.text" and that X is a positive integer. If this is not the case, the function may produce unexpected results.

