You can use the `time.Parse` function to parse a string in the format of `time.RFC3339` and check if the input string is a unix timestamp (a string representation of an int64 number) before calling `time.Parse`. Here is an example of how you can implement the `ParseTime` function:
```
func ParseTime(s string) (time.Time, error) {
    var t time.Time
    var err error

    unixTimestamp, err := strconv.ParseInt(s, 10, 64)
    if err == nil {
        t = time.Unix(unixTimestamp, 0)
    } else {
        t, err = time.Parse(time.RFC3339, s)
    }

    return t, err
}
```
This function first tries to parse the input string `s` as a unix timestamp using the `strconv.ParseInt` function. If this is successful, it will return the `time.Time` value corresponding to the unix timestamp. If not, it will try to parse the input string as a time in the `time.RFC3339` format using the `time.Parse` function. If this also fails, it will return an error.

