Yes, it's possible to build custom Terraform providers that leverage existing providers. A custom provider can wrap or extend another provider to offer additional functionality or adapt to a specific use case. In your case, if you have a service that deploys VMs in AWS, you can build a custom provider that uses the AWS provider under the hood.

Here's an example of how you might approach this:

1. Use the AWS provider as a dependency: In your custom provider code, you would import the AWS provider as a dependency. This allows you to leverage its functionality for creating and managing AWS resources.
2. Define your custom provider schema: You would define your custom provider's schema to include the necessary configuration parameters and resources specific to your use case. You can choose to expose some of the AWS provider's functionality directly or create higher-level abstractions that simplify the interface for your users.
3. Implement CRUD operations: For each resource defined in your custom provider, you would implement the Create, Read, Update, and Delete (CRUD) operations. In these operations, you can call the appropriate functions from the AWS provider to create and manage the underlying AWS resources.
4. Register and distribute your custom provider: Once your custom provider is complete, you would need to register it with Terraform and distribute it to your users, either privately or through the Terraform Registry.

Here's a high-level example of how your custom provider code might look in Go:
```go
package main

import (
  "github.com/hashicorp/terraform-plugin-sdk/v2/helper/schema"
  "github.com/hashicorp/terraform-plugin-sdk/v2/plugin"
  "github.com/yourcustomprovider/aws"
)

func main() {
  plugin.Serve(&plugin.ServeOpts{
    ProviderFunc: func() *schema.Provider {
      return &schema.Provider{
        Schema:         aws.Provider().Schema,
        ResourcesMap:   mergeResourceMaps(aws.Provider().ResourcesMap, customResourcesMap),
        DataSourcesMap: mergeDataSourcesMaps(aws.Provider().DataSourcesMap, customDataSourcesMap),
      }
    },
  })
}

// mergeResourceMaps and mergeDataSourcesMaps functions to merge resource and data source maps
```
Remember that Terraform providers are essentially wrappers around APIs, so you can leverage existing providers to interact with those APIs and build upon them to create custom functionality.

